description.text:
Pikachu pokémon figure, seated on a named hexagon plate.

I wanted to try out my new 3Dprinter, and how well it prints small details and round surfaces. Since the only included filament color that came with the printer was a bright yellow, and In these times of Pokémon Go, what else to print than a Pickachu.

This can be printed without support structures, but beware of the tail. To be safe, try using support.

You will most likely be told by your 3Dprinting software that this model has errors. If your printing software has an auto-correct feature, turn it on, and the Pikachu should print without issues.

NOTE:
3D model data is Copyright Gamefreak, Nintendo and The Pokémon Company 2001-2016.
This is a fan-art project, and all rights to the Pokémon and Pikachu brand and name belongs to Nintento and the Pokémon Company.

Printer:

XYZprinting da Vinci 1.0 PRO 3-in-1

Resolution:

0.4mm nozzle, 0.25mm layer height

Infill:

15% (10% should do as well)

Notes:

You may need rafts if your printer has problems making prints stick, and support to ensure proper printing of the last tail section.

I printed this without support and without rafts, using ABS at 210 C nozzle and 90 C plate, with 15% hexagon infill.

Making this Pikachu

I started searching for a sufficiently detailed Pikachu model to print, but to my surprise, no such model existed. A few came close, but I did not like the pose of Pikachu. In order to ensure a reasonably robust print, and the ability to print without support structure, I realized that I had to make my own Pikachu Pokémon 3D model.

As I have close to zero modelling experience or skills, the task of modelling Pikachu from scratch was not a possibility. Fortunately, with the Pokemon Go game comes a lot of great 3D models which are freely available to download (just remember to give all attribution to Nintendo etc. when used): http://roestudios.co.uk/project/3d-pokemon-models/

I now had a good Pikachu 3D model, but this was posed similar to the ones I already found in several 3Dprint archives with Pokemon models. After a bit more searching, I struck gold in this poseable Pikachu model made by Haolink on Deviantart: http://haolink.deviantart.com/art/Pikachu-MMD-3D-Model-eye-posable-557647939

With the poseable model, I now had complete freedom to make Pikachu take a seat and lay its arms on its stomach.
Then came the hard part of exporting the model as an STL. I make write a blog post about this at some point on my blog: http://blog.mivia.dk, but for now lets say that a lot of import/export was going on between the programs: Mmd, PmxEditor, Blender, Sketchup and XYZware pro.

I had to completely redraw and re-attach the tail of Pikachu in Sketchup, which is also where I added the hexagon plate and the text. If you investigate the stl, you will notice that this is not a clean model, as several surfaces are in collision or missing. I could clean this up in sketchup, but this would most likely take hours.

Let me know if you are able to print using this stl as it is now, so I know if it will be worth the effort to do a complete clean-up of the model.

The poseable Pikachu model opened in PmxEditor I initially made this pose in Mmd, but something made it impossible to import in in PmxEditor, so i had to re-do it directly in PmxEditor The finished model (with some internal errors still left to correct) assembled in Sketchup

description.text:
Hi all! I did this UV lamp a few months ago and now I want to share it with you guys. I will try to explain it as clearly as I can. If you dont understand something just feel free to ask me as English is not my main language :)

This project is supposed to be cheap so the entire lamp should cost less than 8$ if you find good offers.

WHAT DO YOU NEED?

  • 6x UV high power leds.

I bought that ones 395-400nm and it works fine so there's no need of shorter wavelength because you can hurt your hands. The only important thing here is to choose the ones with 16mm rounded base to ensure it will fit well. (COST: 5$)

http://www.ebay.com/itm/1-10-20-50-pcs-3W-High-Power-UV-ultraviolet-365nm-395nm-420nm-LED-Lamp-Light-/221810182099

  • 1x microUSB step-up converter.

I decided to use this power supply because everybody have microUSB cables and it's a cheap module to get that extra voltage to drive the leds. If you want to use another type of power supply you will have to edit rear face because it is made to fit this model (COST 2$)

http://www.banggood.com/es/2A-DC-DC-Boost-Step-Up-Conversion-Module-MicroUSB-2-24V-To-5V-28V-12V-9V-24V-p-1019102.html

  • 3x 1 Ohm 1W resistors.

  • 1x Prototype PCB

This is optional. If you want to wire all easily you should buy it. You can find it easily and it cost me less than 1$ for a 10x pack.

  • Cable to wire everything together

INSTRUCTIONS

I'm sorry because I didn't take pictures of the assembling process but I think it's easy to do it.

First of all you need to print the led holder part. As you can see it has 6 pairs of holes, each pair of holes is for one led so you must wire all leds and pass the cables through the holes (One for negative and one for positive). When you have all the leds in position you can glue them to ensure they won't fall.

Now you have to wire leds and resistors like the picture shows. Left and right end of the circuit is going to be wired to the step-up converter so ensure the cable you use is large enough to reach the bottom of the lamp.

When you finish the wires, pass the two end cables of the circuit through the rear face tunnel. This is a good moment to glue the step-up converter to the rear face and ensure you can connect the microUSB cable without problems.

To finish it you just have to wire the cables of the led circuit to the step-up converter. The cable on the leds side goes to OUT+ and the cable on the resistors side goes to OUT-. Before assembling the last parts you should connect it to power and test it. THIS IS THE MOST IMPORTANT PART!!! Adjust the screw of the step-up converter to get the best performace. It's vital to spend some time here to get the best result. If you have a multimeter I got the best performace at 7V output aprox. On every try of configuration you should wait at least 3 mins to ensure it has enough current because it could seem everything it's ok but after a few minutes the leds could start blinking because of lack of current so spend as much time as you need to ensure it's stable.

When all is done assemble the led holder to the core part (no need to glue it) and put some glue in the core holes to fix the rear and front faces to the core part.

And that's all my friends!! Now you are ready to test it or gift it to your girlfriend :)

title: Easy swap system for Micro 105 FPV Quadcopter

description.text:
First of all, credit goes out to Punkkills for designing the Micro 105 frame which has been my favorite frame to fly, adapt and build upon. I'm new to 3d design and I could not have made this from scratch.

Updates:

18-3-2017

  • Added a skillfully painted schematic for Kanata :)

31-1-2017

  • Tested out the version with grommets and it has way less power, wouldn't recommend it!

10-1-2017

  • Added a version which supports 8mm rubber grommets

29-12-2016

  • Added a battery holder for Nanotech 600 (untested)

26-12-2016

  • Added a 7mm version of the frame by request, not tested but should work.
  • Added the CLI dump as a text file.

Why this remix?

3D printing quadcopter frames is convenient, but I always end up breaking a lot of them. Whilst the costs of printing a new one is low, it takes precious time to change the frame which could also be used for flying instead. What I wanted to achieve was a system which allows for quick frame swapping in the field, so I could just bring a few spare frames and parts, keeping repair time down to a minimum.

Features:

  • Easy to swap to a new frame (takes around 2 minutes)
  • Modular parts so if you break a battery mount, you can easily replace it and keep flying.
  • Easily adaptable to different FC's, batteries, camera's, and even frames.
  • Good protection of electronics and the cloverleaf antenna if you use the 'Mulletmod'.
  • Great performance, check it out here :)

Build instructions:

Requirements:

  • You are going to need 2x M3 nylon bolts and nuts.
  • Motors need to be direct soldered to the FC, there is no room for connectors.
  • Mullet mod for the cam/vtx is recommended, but I have included a normal camera mount if you haven't done a mulletmod before. (if you haven't, look it up on youtube it's perfect)

tip: solder the motors to the underside of the FC. This allows for easy soldering access when replacing a motor. Use some drops of hotglue on the solder points and on the front corners because this is what the FC will rest on when it is 'sandwiched'. :)

The idea is the flightcontroller is secured to the Cameramount and NOT to the frame. You can use double sided tape and a bit of hotglue. The Cameramount+FC is then attached to the frame using 2 nylon bolts. On the bottom side of the frame, the batterybracket is then secured with the 2 nylon nuts.

The batteryholder is to be superglued to the batterybracket. Make a few of them so it can't cause you downtime if the mount would snap off in a crash.

Now when you want to change the frame, perform maintenance or repairs, you just unscrew the 2 bolts, and off come all the electronics!

*almost forgot: there is a little 'tab' at the front of the frame, this is to protect the front of the battery and prevent it from shooting forward in a crash. You can heat this with a lighter and bend it in shape. (careful not to burn your fingers)

Designed for parts:

Micro SciSky or similar (preferably with integrated receiver to save weight and space)
FX798T or similar (if you have a request, let me know, tx03?)
8.5mm motors (Preferably the better ones like MMW, Spintechs, etc.)
Battery holder designed to fit Graphene 600 (Again, if you have a request, let me know)
Hubsan clear props (ebay) (my favorite)
65mm gemfans also fit perfectly (on the 8.5mm version), but I don't like them.

Wait, what..?

Did I forget anything? Do you have any questions?
Suggestions for batteries/camera mounts?

Let me know in the comments!

Happy building, flying, and quickswapping it! :)

description.text:
If your printer does not have an acrylic cover, chances are you have considered it, but you do not have access to a laser cutter, and any existing solutions involved modifying the printer itself.

Well no more, the Practically Invisible Front Cover does not require any printer modifications. Buy any off the shelf acrylic sheet, and transform it into a front cover in half an hour. No laser cutter required.

What is this Black Magic?

The Practically Invisible Front Cover(tm) will preserve the clean look of your printer, and asks nothing more than a few seconds of your time to lock in the front cover whenever it is removed. This is done by attaching 4 swivel locks to the acrylic sheet itself, it's clean, it's easy, it's awesome.

What do I need to do, aside from printing the swivel locks (CH01)?

Use a hot solder to burn 4 holes into the acrylic sheet, it will only take a minute. 4 pages of very educational instructions included.

Inspiration

I am always inspired by the practical simplicity of IKEA furnitures that uses plastic mounts to lock things into place, and I have a feeling one of those IKEA things uses swivel locks.

Please post your makes

It helps me to improve further when you share your makes, and it helps people with measurements for their printers. The measurements provided by me is only applicable for Ultimaker 2 printers.

description.text:
Bought a very small hookah recently, but the bubbles were clogging the hose with water. Commercial diffuser would not fit inside and even if it would, there water level is not high enough to use it. This aerator is designed to make the bubbles smaller so the water won't splash inside the jar while keeping very small size and low water level. As with other diffusers there is a distinct change of sound while smoking, hookah is quieter and smaller bubbles should give better filtration of the smoke too.  
It should fit on pipes with outer diameter 11-12mm. Inside the flange is also a groove for o-ring, but in my case (11.5mm) the aerator stays on the pipe even without it.

Printing of this thing is a bit tricky. Prepare a lot of patience and have your printer well calibrated. The whole aerator is less than 30mm big to fit even into a narrow bottleneck and more than seventy holes have only 2.5mm dia. Few of them will get clogged during the print (you can be sure) so prepare your self a small drill (2-2.5mm) to open them again. If you keep them clogged smoking the hookah may get harder and unpleasant.   
Although it have a sort of semicircular shape it have to be printed without the supports, because otherwise it would be very complicated to get the support out from the inside. But the print can be finished succesfully even without them (you will have to live with few imperfections though :D ).   
The particular diffuser on the photographs was made of ABS with 0.5mm nozzle, 0.25mm thick layers so the openings were drilled and whole thing sanded afterwards. I think that 0.35mm nozzle, 0.15mm layer would give better results but stil there will be a lot of overflow.   
You can put inside the flange a rubber o-ring with inside dia aprox. 10-11mm. The installation of the aerator will get more complicated but it will keep its position on the pipe and you won't have to use glue.

description.text:
I designed these to provide some unique lighting for a party. The design was made in OpenSCAD.

You'll need to buy a few things to make these and links to amazon are at the bottom. They're not affiliate links and it doesn't really matter where you buy them from I was just providing a direction to start with.

You'll need:
-3d printer + filament...well...yea
-g4 bulb socket
-g4 110v led bulb
-round 2 prong electrical socket
-Wire Strippers
-super glue

Assembly steps:
1) Print part
2) Clear the wire hole for the g4 socket. With a small screwdriver or something similar break through the filament strings bellow the g4 socket hole. It's where there is a 100% overhang part of the design, so there will be some strings but just break them apart to clear the path for the g4 socket wires to feed through.
3) Feed through the wires for the g4 socket
4) cut off ~0.5" from the end of the wires and strip 0.75" of insulation off of what's left
5) Remove the two screws from the electrical socket and take the black outter sleeve off.
6) Feed the two wires through through the black outer sleeve so that the enter the skinny end and exit the wide end
7) Wrap each bare wire around one of the screw terminals for the socket and tighten down...wrap them around clockwise so that as the screw tightens it further tightens the wire
8) reattach the black outer sleeve to the electrical socket with the two screws you removed earlier
9) Push the plug into its hole in the 3d printed part. I found that rotating just the plug ~360 degrees before pushing it in helped the wires feed into the cavity easier.
10) When you're happy with the alignment of the plug and the 3d printed part apply superglue to the ridges of the electrical socket to attach the socket to the 3d printer part.

This idea came to me a few years ago when I was taking a lot of photos of birds in flight. While thinking of a better way to follow fast flying birds, I was remembering my teenage years of hunting birds with a shotgun. The idea is borrowed from the open sights on guns. It is a lot easier to follow motion with an open sight rather than a scope which is what the viewfinder on SLR cameras is similar to.

I am using the flash Hot Shoe mount on the camera to mount this sight, so you will not be able to attach a flash to that hot shoe or use a popup flash that SLR's like my Canon 60D have. I measure a 68mm offset between the center line of the lens & the bottom of the attached V-Sight.

There are basically 3 parts to create this sight, and take 1 to 1.5 hours to print depending on the configuration you print.

  1. The camera mount that slides in the flash Hot Shoe mount
  2. The Barrel with front & rear sights
  3. The tightening Nut to tighten the sight down.
  4. Optional: 15mm plastic Wrench to tighten the nut onto the camera mount
    (You might still need to use an adjustable wrench to initially get the nut threaded on the camera mount)

CameraMountAndTightenNut_rev22.scad is the file to create the Camera Mount & tightening Nut. I initially used the Standard M10 screw thread pitch of 1.5, but found 2.5 pitch worked better for my finished print. I used the threads.scad module from http://dkprojects.net/openscad-threads/ to generate the threads. For the tightening nut I scaled it up 15% (1.15) in the X & Y to get the best fit for my printer. I painted the little orange dots using this indoor/outdoor multisurface paint from Walmart. https://www.plaidonline.com/apple-barrel-multi-surface-satin-acrylic-paints-ou/209/21961E/product.htm

V_Sight_Rev39.scad is the file to create the sighting barrel. This has quite a few variables you can change. The 2 variables that will affect your sighting distance the most which are V_HT (Height of Rear Sight) & Len (Length of Barrel).

There are 3 different Sight types.
SightType = 0; //Simple Bead on the Front of the Sight

SightType = 1; //Drilled for using an inserted sight of your choice. The file FrontSights_Rev1.scad creates sights for this. I print about 12 at a time & choose the best one as some print better than others on my printer. You could also use a piece of 3mm filament if you have it, an M3 screw, cutoff a piece of a nozzle from an air can which is 3mm. There are probably a lot of other things you could find to use. The setscrew I used is a M2.5x10mm, but 8mm length will work.

SightType = 2; //Adjustable Front Side sight. This was my latest idea for the front sight and probably easier to adjust than type 1. You use a machine screw mounted thru the slotted hole & put a jam nut, nut or locknut to hold it at the level you want. If you are using metric hardware, M3 or M2.5 screws with a length of 12mm or more. For imperial sizes, #6x1/2" is probably the easiest to find. #5 or #4 will work if you can find them. The photo shown has a #6x1/2" machine screw and regular nut.

To initially adjust the sight, I would put your camera on a tripod with a lens attached. Attach this V_Sight to your flash shoe, but leave loose enough if you need to rotate it a little left or right. I think the sight should work the same with whatever lens you use. Look thru your viewfinder & the V_Sight to see how close they look & adjust accordingly.

I have included the openscad source files & some sample STL file models. The main V_Sight openscad file I made customizable for 10 of the variables, but there are a few other variables you can change if using the openscad file on your computer.

It might take a little getting use to, but with some practice I think this sight holds promise for getting better fast action shots.

print_settings.Notes:: Print it with "build plate only" supports, upright. Both Cura and  S3D support that option. It's an easy print, done on my junky Anet A8 with stock fan duct. I used PLA plastic, it works OK for PLA printing with bed temperature about 65C and fan 100%. But bed temperature over 80C is too hot for PLA duct, use PETG or something like that.

description.text:
Why

All fan ducts suck. This one sucks less (I hope!). There are several reasons: first, it does not restrict air flow (each branch cross-section is 1/2 of the inlet). Second, it maintains laminar air flow. Third, it provides even cooling from both sides (good for PLA plastic). Fourth: it's completely customizable, just load it into FreeCAD 0.16 and edit variables in cf spreadsheet.

Designed for Anet A8 (Hesine, Omni, etc), but you can change parameters to fit it almost anywhere.

Use heat shield

This fan duct cools heat block a lot, so insulate it or use some kind of heat shield (I made one from cotton stripes and kapton tape). Look at the temperature graph: without heat shield temperature swings cause serious wobble that looks almost exactly like z-woble, but wobbling disappears when heat shield is installed.

There is a gap between heatblock wires and duct's right branch, heat shield fits there just fine.

PID tuning

Do not skip this step. After installation of fan duct run PID tuning as described here: http://reprap.org/wiki/PID_Tuning with fan running at your usuall fan speed and save new parameters into your EEPROM (or, better, create various PID parameters for various plastics types and set them in gcode startup scripts).

How to customize

Use FreeCAD 0.16 (install from web, don't use stale versions from repos). Open freecad source file, switch to cf spreadsheet and edit variables. If FreeCAD is too slow to recompute on the fly, install Lattice2 extension, turn off recomputes, edit spreadsheet (look at the drawing for variable names), click recompute. Export helix_fan_duct_v7 object as STL.

Note that S3D complains about self-intersecting surfaces. This is due to how FreeCAD handles helix objects, but it does not matter printing-wise. It will print ok.

I tried :

  • LG 360

description.text:
Gif link: http://i.imgur.com/FgFF2AQ.gifv

A Pusheen with a planetary gearbox inside. I made this as a christmas gift. It was made on a Makerbot Replicator 2X with grey ABS, so your settings and results may vary.

Print:
(1) Ring Gear
(1) Gear Carrier
(1) Rear Bar
(1) Crank
(1) Inner Gear
(5) Outer Gears
(5) Gear Backings

Assembly:

  1. Insert the gear carrier into the ring gear.
  2. Insert the 5 outer gears and the 1 inner gear into the gear carrier.
  3. Insert the gear backings into the outer gears. Apply super glue inside the gear if necessary to attach the backing, but do not get super glue on the outside or any moving surface.
  4. Apply super glue to the inside of the inner gear.
  5. Attach the rear bar with super glue, being careful not to super glue any moving surfaces.
  6. Insert the crank through the hole in the rear bar, where it will mate with the inner gear via super glue. Do not let this super glue spill up into the gear carrier or rear bar, as this will immobilize the gearbox.

Tips:
-You may need to sand some pieces for smooth operation.
-Assemble the model with no gears and test that it runs smoothly before applying any glue.
-Pusheen face done with acrylic paint.

For today's #3DPrintmas model I'm bringing Bugdroid to the party. Bugdroid is the mascot for the Android operating system. He's a pretty simple shape but he's pretty recognizable and fun.

I created it in Fusion 360 by taking an SVG file of his outline, I cut it in half and revolved the body around the center axis to give it the cylindrical body.

Then I handed it off to my wife for painting. She used a sponge with some acrylic paints for the green all over the body. Then she used a paintbrush for the black eyes and she also painted black around the insides of the head and body to give it a darker look inside that crack.

When assembled this series of objects will make a hand harness perfect for mindfulness exercises centering around the movement of your hand. It is designed to feel strange enough to make you notice your own motion, but not uncomfortable.

This project has three pieces: hook, side anchor, and circle anchor. The hook and side anchor are both printed in two pieces and meant to be glued together to make one completed object. You will also need a form of elastic string. I recommend stretchy monofilament used for beading and found in most craft stores or online.   
You will need 3 prints of the hook, 2 prints of the side anchor, and 1 print of the circle anchors. This project is printed in PLA with two shells and a 20% infill.  
The easiest way to put this together is to look at the drawings of the set up above and follow those, but just to be sure, below is a written description.  
Once all the pieces are printed and glued together as instructed, you will want to set the hook pieces in between your fingers with the ring on the back of your hand. The side anchor pieces are for the space between your thumb and forefinger and also on the opposite side of the hand past the pinky. The circle anchor piece with 4 circles goes on the back of your hand and should be oriented so that it is longer vertically than horizontally. The hook from the webbing between your middle and ring finger should connect to the top most circle with the elastic. Both the hook from the webbing between your forefinger and middle finger and the side anchor between your forefinger and thumb should share the circle nearest them. The hook from between the ring finger and pinky should share an anchor circle with the side anchor. The bottom most circle will connect to the top most ring on the three-ring circle anchor on the back of your wrist. The side rings of that same three ring circle will connect to a different circle in the center of the underside of your wrist. The top ring of this three ring circle anchor will connect to another circle anchor oriented point down. The other sides of this third three ring circle anchor will connect to their respective side anchors.
